A griffin (or griffon, depending on the English spelling) is a mythological creature with the body of a lion and the head and wings of an eagle. It is a common figure in the mythology and art of various cultures, often associated with vigilance and the protection of treasures.
Characteristics:
Body:
The lower body of the griffin is that of a lion, including its tail and hind legs.
Head and Wings:
The upper body is that of an eagle, with a sharp beak, piercing eyes, and feathers.
Additional Attributes:
In some depictions, it is also attributed with pointed ears and eagle-like foreclaws.
Symbolism and Meaning:
Guardian:
Griffons are known to be guardians of treasures and riches, especially gold.
Strength and Courage:
Combining the strength of the lion and the sharpness of the eagle, the griffin symbolizes power, courage, and vigilance. Connection to the Sun:
In some cultures, the griffin is associated with the sun and light, due to the eagle's majestic nature.
Origin:
Griffins are believed to have ancient origins, possibly in the Middle East or Asia.
Depictions of griffins are found in the art and mythology of various civilizations, including Greek, Roman, and Persian.
There is speculation that the image of the griffin may have been inspired by dinosaur fossils.

The Wastes are home to all manner of terrible creatures, mutated from what were once the humble creatures of the forests. Whether this was by design, genetic mutation, or simply through exposure to chaotic magics is unknown.

This is a collection of mutated beasts, designed for Fantasy and Post-Apocalyptic Wargaming and RPGs. They are truly massive beasts, and so are provided both whole, in kit form, and with hollowed out versions to allow you to chose the right set for your needs. These were made whilst making my toad-dragon (link below), as each time I looked at it, it made me think of a different animal! I saw a rat, molerat, and hippo, and here they are!

I love settings in post apocalyptic fallout shelters, where desert mole rats have mutated into massive beasts, so have a particular fondness for the mole-rat monster here - perfect for creating a monstrous mount for your post apocalyptic raiders or travelling merchants!

The Toad Dragon can be found here:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/chaos-toad-dragon

These models come without rider or saddle, and are designed to be kit-bashed with your favourite fantasy range. These parts are also compatible with the bits from the Toad Dragon, and so would complement it nicely.

Please see my other designs for other wargaming STLS, including maggots, tics and flies suitable for adding even more detail to this model, or to decorate your army's bases.

I am an amateur enthusiast 3D designer, and appreciate all support and constructive feedback. Please check out my other designs for more wargame models, and please consider following me, post a make, and enjoy my models. If you would like to support my work, please leave a comment, like the design, or make a donation via my profile! Thanks!

As famine struck the dark forests of Jotunheim, Wolf-Eater scaled the impossible cliffs of Ymir's Brow, descending into the lowlands of Midgard and sating his hunger on the tribes of men.

I wanted to make a proper Norse dragon. I really liked the idea of an antlered forest wyrm with vestigial wings adapted to climbing giant trees. Currently using this guy as the center of an RPG storyline. He's scaled to 15mm (making him rather massive) so he can be used with my Pocket-Tactics models, but he'd make a good dragon for heroic scale (25-30mm gaming) as well.
